        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "What if my parent's income is just over the limit?",
            "answer": "They may still qualify through the net income test. Alaska allows deductions for medical expenses over $35/month, housing costs up to $1,189/month, and 20% of earned income. These deductions often bring seniors below the net income limit even when gross income seems too high."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can my parent keep their house if they get SNAP?",
            "answer": "Yes. Your parent's primary home and the lot it sits on don't count toward the $4,500 asset limit. Neither do household goods, burial plots, retirement accounts, or life insurance."
          },
          {
            "question": "How much will my parent receive each month?",
            "answer": "The amount depends on net income after deductions and household size. Generally, about $30 less in benefits for every $100 more in net income. Seniors often get more because of medical and shelter deductions that younger households don't qualify for."
          },
          {
            "question": "What's different if all adults in the household are 60+?",
            "answer": "They qualify for ESAP (Elderly Simplified Application Project), which means easier paperwork, recertification every 36 months instead of annually, and no interim reports unless someone starts working or wins more than $4,500 gambling."
          },
          {
            "question": "What can't my parent buy with SNAP benefits?",
            "answer": "SNAP cannot be used for alcohol, tobacco, vitamins, hot prepared foods, or non-food items like soap or paper products. It can be used at most grocery stores and many farmers markets."
          },
          {
            "question": "Do we need to report changes after approval?",
            "answer": "Yes, but it depends on your parent's situation. ESAP households (all adults 60+/disabled) only need to report if adults start working or if they win more than $4,500 from gambling or lottery. Other households must report income and household changes within 10 days."
          }
        ],
        "phone": "800-478-7778",
