        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "Can my parent keep their house if they qualify for PACE?",
            "answer": "Yes. Your parent's primary home doesn't count toward the $2,000 asset limit for Medicaid funding. PACE is specifically designed to help people stay in their own homes instead of moving to nursing facilities."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if my parent's income is just over the Medicaid limit?",
            "answer": "Arkansas allows Income Trusts for applicants whose income exceeds Medicaid limits. Contact a DHS caseworker to discuss this option. Your parent can also pay privately for PACE services if they don't qualify for Medicaid funding but meet the medical criteria."
          },
          {
            "question": "Does my parent have to give up their current Medicare plan?",
            "answer": "Yes. Your parent cannot be enrolled in Medicare Advantage, Medicare prescription drug plans, or certain other programs while in PACE. PACE becomes their Medicare and Medicaid coverage, providing more comprehensive services than typical Medicare plans."
          },
          {
            "question": "How is PACE different from regular home health care?",
            "answer": "PACE provides comprehensive care coordination — one team manages all medical care, transportation, adult day care, home services, and medications. Regular home health typically provides specific services a few times per week. PACE participants average 76 years old with multiple complex conditions."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if my parent needs nursing home care later?",
            "answer": "PACE covers nursing home care when medically necessary. Because the same team manages all care, transitions are coordinated rather than requiring separate applications and provider changes."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can my parent choose their own doctors in PACE?",
            "answer": "Your parent's care will be provided by PACE's interdisciplinary medical team. This team approach allows for better coordination but means your parent may need to change from their current doctors to PACE providers."
          }
        ],
