        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "Does my parent's Social Security count against the income limit?",
            "answer": "Yes, Social Security benefits count as income. However, medical expenses over $35/month (including Medicare premiums, prescriptions, and doctor visits) are deducted from countable income, which can help your parent qualify or increase their benefits."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can Mom keep her house and still qualify?",
            "answer": "Yes, your parent's home doesn't count toward the $4,500 asset limit regardless of its value. The limit applies to cash, bank accounts, and non-exempt property."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if my parent lives with me but we buy groceries separately?",
            "answer": "If your parent buys and prepares food separately, they can apply as a one-person household even if living with you. The key is whether food is purchased and prepared together — separate grocery shopping means separate household for SNAP purposes."
          },
          {
            "question": "How much will my parent actually receive each month?",
            "answer": "It depends on their net income after deductions. Maximum benefit is $298/month for one person, but most seniors receive $100-200/month. The exact amount is calculated by subtracting 30% of net income from the maximum benefit."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can SNAP benefits be used at restaurants?",
            "answer": "Yes, if your parent is 60+ or disabled, they may qualify for the Restaurant Meals Program, which allows EBT use at participating restaurants. Not all restaurants participate — check with your local DHS office for locations."
          },
          {
            "question": "What happens if my parent's income is just over the limit?",
            "answer": "Medical deductions can make the difference. If your parent pays more than $35/month for medical expenses (including Medicare premiums), those costs are subtracted from countable income. Even small medical deductions can bring income under the limit."
          }
        ],
