        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "What if my parent's income is just over the limit?",
            "answer": "Income limits vary slightly between local Community-Based Organizations. If your parent is close to the limit, contact your county's CBO directly — they may use different calculations or have updated limits."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can my parent get help if utilities are included in their rent?",
            "answer": "Yes, but they must provide their lease agreement showing the energy burden. Different rules apply for subsidized versus unsubsidized housing, so bring the lease for your CBO to review."
          },
          {
            "question": "What happens if the power company threatens to shut off service?",
            "answer": "Apply immediately for crisis assistance (up to $500). Crisis help covers shut-offs, disconnections, fuel depletion, or life-threatening situations. Your parent can receive both regular seasonal assistance and crisis help in the same year."
          },
          {
            "question": "Does my parent need to pay anything back?",
            "answer": "No, LIHEAP benefits are not loans. The money goes directly to the utility company or fuel vendor and never needs to be repaid."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if my parent heats with propane or wood instead of electric or gas?",
            "answer": "LIHEAP covers all energy sources including propane, wood, and pellets. The benefit amount varies by energy source, so bring documentation of your parent's heating method when applying."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can my parent apply every year?",
            "answer": "Yes, but they must reapply each year during the designated seasonal periods. They can receive one regular heating benefit, one cooling benefit, and one crisis benefit per season per household each year."
          }
        ],
