        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "Can Mom keep her house if she qualifies for ALTCS?",
            "answer": "Yes, if your mom intends to return home or certain family members live there. The home is exempt as long as the equity is $752,000 or less. If equity exceeds this amount, she may still qualify but will need to address the excess equity."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if Dad's income is just over the limit?",
            "answer": "He may still qualify through an Income Only Trust (also called a Miller Trust). This legal tool allows excess income to be placed in trust, bringing his countable income below the limit. You'll need an elder law attorney to set this up properly."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can I get paid to care for my parent through ALTCS?",
            "answer": "Yes, ALTCS allows family members to be paid as caregivers through Medicaid. Even better, this 'Difficulty of Care' income doesn't count against your parent's income limits for eligibility, making it easier for families to qualify while keeping care in the home."
          },
          {
            "question": "How does the clinical assessment work?",
            "answer": "A Pre-Admission Screening (PAS) evaluates whether your parent needs daily help with activities like bathing, dressing, eating, toileting, transferring, or mobility. They also assess cognitive deficits from conditions like dementia. Having a diagnosis alone isn't enough — your parent must demonstrate actual functional limitations."
          },
          {
            "question": "What happens if Dad gave away money in the past few years?",
            "answer": "ALTCS looks back at financial transfers and may impose penalty periods where your dad can't receive benefits. Penalty amounts vary by county: $8,666.72/month in Maricopa, Pima, and Pinal counties, $8,132.22/month in other Arizona counties. Each transfer is evaluated individually."
          },
          {
            "question": "Does ALTCS cover memory care and assisted living?",
            "answer": "Yes, ALTCS covers assisted living, memory care, and skilled nursing facilities, as well as in-home services. The goal is to provide care in the least restrictive setting that meets your parent's needs — many people use ALTCS to stay in their own homes longer."
          }
        ],
