        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "Can my parent keep their house if they qualify for HUSKY C?",
            "answer": "Yes. Your parent's primary residence doesn't count toward the $1,600 asset limit, so they can keep their home and still qualify for HUSKY C."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if my parent's income is just over the limit?",
            "answer": "They may still qualify through 'spend-down.' Connecticut allows people to deduct medical expenses from their income to meet the eligibility threshold. Apply anyway — DSS will calculate if this option works."
          },
          {
            "question": "How is HUSKY C different from Medicare?",
            "answer": "HUSKY C covers services Medicare doesn't, especially long-term care like home health aides, adult day programs, and extended nursing home stays. Your parent can have both Medicare and HUSKY C."
          },
          {
            "question": "What happens to my parent's retirement accounts?",
            "answer": "IRAs and 401(k)s count toward the $1,600 asset limit. Your parent may need to spend down these accounts first, though there are rules about how quickly this must happen."
          },
          {
            "question": "Does HUSKY C have a waiting list?",
            "answer": "No. Unlike some Medicaid waiver programs, HUSKY C is an entitlement program. If your parent qualifies, they receive coverage immediately upon approval."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can immigrants qualify for HUSKY C?",
            "answer": "Qualified non-citizens can apply, but most must wait 5 years after receiving their status. Refugees and asylees don't have this waiting period and can apply immediately."
          }
        ],
