        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "Can Mom keep her house if she qualifies for Medicaid?",
            "answer": "Yes, while she's alive. The home is exempt if equity is $730,000 or less and she intends to return (even from a nursing home). However, Utah may try to recover Medicaid costs from the home's sale after death through estate recovery."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if Dad's income is just over the limit for home care?",
            "answer": "He may still qualify for nursing home Medicaid, which has no strict income limit — most income just goes toward care costs. Or explore spend-down options where excess income goes toward medical expenses to qualify."
          },
          {
            "question": "If my parents are married and one needs nursing home care, will they lose everything?",
            "answer": "No. The spouse staying home can keep up to $157,920 in assets (minimum $31,584) and enough income to live independently. Only the spouse needing care has their assets and income counted toward the $2,000/$45 monthly limits."
          },
          {
            "question": "How long does it take to get approved for home care services?",
            "answer": "Processing time isn't specified, but you'll need a clinical assessment after applying to determine which services your parent qualifies for. Home-based waivers may have waitlists, so apply early if avoiding nursing home placement is the goal."
          },
          {
            "question": "What's the difference between regular Medicaid and the long-term care programs?",
            "answer": "Regular Medicaid (ABD) covers medical services but typically doesn't include long-term care like personal care or nursing homes. You need to apply separately for nursing home Medicaid or home-based waivers to get long-term care services covered."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can we transfer assets to other family members to qualify faster?",
            "answer": "Be careful — Medicaid has a 5-year lookback period for asset transfers. Transfers made within 5 years of applying can create penalty periods where your parent is ineligible for benefits. Consult an elder law attorney before transferring assets."
          }
        ],
